vernment partners in making recommendations\r\nfor policy, actions and programs.\r\n\r\nThe first FPC was formed 30 years ago in Knoxville, Tennessee, launched by a university student project.\r\nIn the 1990s and early 2000s, several more were formed. Recently, a number of federal grants have required\r\nthat the applicants work with a local FPC or form one, if none exists.\r\n\r\nSome FPCs are government-appointed bodies, others (like FPCSA) are 501c3 organizations, and many are\r\nindependent grass-roots organizations. Whatever the structure, they work to focus a community’s resources\r\nand knowledge to build a healthier, more accessible and resilient local food system for all.\r\n\r\nMore information is at the\r\n<a href=\"http://www.jhsph.edu/research/centers-and-institutes/johns-hopkins-center-for-a-livable-future/projects/index.html\">\r\nJohns Hopkins Center for a Livable Future</a>.\r\n<h2>What do you mean by Food System?</h2>\r\nA “systems” view of factors relating to food and nutrition looks beyond symptoms\r\n(such as hunger or diet-related disease) to see how factors interact. This view can help trace root\r\ncauses and suggest innovative policy solutions. Here is one representation of a food system,\r\nfrom Agricultural Urbanism: HB Lanarc publishers.\r\n\r\n<img alt=\"Growing, Processing, Transportation &amp; Storage, Distribution,  Eating &amp; Celebrating, Waste Recovery and Education all interact to create a food system\" src=\"http://foodpolicysa.org/?p=14\" width=\"42\" height=\"42\" />\r\n<h2>Members</h2>\r\nMembers of FPCSA are drawn from diverse sectors of the food system. Membership slots are limited, and applications\r\nare received only for open sectors. Volunteering with a standing committee, a working group, or events is a good way to get\r\nacquainted with the organization to decide whether to apply for a slot you might qualify for. It’s also a way for us to get\r\nto know you, your interests and your strengths.\r\n\r\nBoard\r\n<h2>Meetings</h2>\r\n&nbsp;','About','','inherit','open','open','','8-revision-v1','','','2013-12-03 20:11:27','2013-12-03 20:11:27','',8,'/11',0,'revision','',0),(12,3,'2013-12-06 18:26:26','2013-12-07 00:26:26','<h2>Mission</h2>\nThe Food Policy Council of San Antonio serves as a stakeholder forum to support a healthy, sustainable, and just local food system for people, the environment, the economy and community; gathers and disseminates information for all who work toward that goal in the San Antonio area; and advocates for policy improvements relating to food.\n\nMany organizations exist to focus on programs. In order to address the entirety of the food system, we instead gather and provide information, and formulate policy positions. For those organizations and for all levels of government, we can be a resource to research issues, uncover best practices, and connect diverse stakeholders.\n<h2>History</h2>\nThe Food Policy Council of San Antonio was formed by the San Antonio Metropolitan Health District, under a Communities Putting Prevention to Work (CPPW) grant, from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, and the Department of Health and Human Services. The grant was awarded in March 2010. A steering committee drawn from Metro Health staff and the community developed an application and selection process open to the entire community. The Food Policy Council held its first meeting in October of that year.\n\nIn May 2012, the Food Policy Council of San Antonio incorporated as a Texas nonprofit, and in August 2013 we were designated a 501c3 organization by the IRS.\n\nFPCSA is organized around categories drawn from sectors of the food system.\n<h2>What is a Food Policy Council?</h2>\nFood Policy Councils (FPCs) bring together stakeholders from diverse community sectors to examine how well the current local food system is working for people’s health and well-being, and then develop policy recommendations to improve it.\n\nFood Policy Councils work closely with local and state government partners in making recommendations for policy, actions and programs.\n\nThe first FPC was formed 30 years ago in Knoxville, Tennessee, launched by a university student project. In the 1990s and early 2000s, several more were formed. Recently, a number of federal grants have required that the applicants work with a local FPC or form one, if none exists.\n\nSome FPCs are government-appointed bodies, others (like FPCSA) are 501c3 organizations, and many are independent grass-roots organizations. Whatever the structure, they work to focus a community’s resources and knowledge to build a healthier, more accessible and resilient local food system for all.\n\nMore information is at the <a href=\"http://www.jhsph.edu/research/centers-and-institutes/johns-hopkins-center-for-a-livable-future/projects/index.html\"> Johns Hopkins Center for a Livable Future</a>.\n<h2>What do you mean by Food System?</h2>\nA “systems” view of factors relating to food and nutrition looks beyond symptoms (such as hunger or diet-related disease) to see how factors interact. This view can help trace root causes and suggest innovative policy solutions. Here is one representation of a food system, from Agricultural Urbanism: HB Lanarc publishers.\n\n<img alt=\"Lots of things make a up food network\" src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Agricultural-Urbanism.png\" />\n<h2>Members</h2>\n<ul>\n	<li>Members of FPCSA are drawn from diverse sectors of the food system. Membership slots are limited, and applications are received only for open sectors. Volunteering with a standing committee, a working group, or events is a good way to get acquainted with the organization to decide whether to apply for a slot you might qualify for. It’s also a way for us to get to know you, your interests and your strengths.</li>\n	<li>Board</li>\n</ul>\n','About','','inherit','open','open','','8-autosave-v1','','','2013-12-06 18:26:26','2013-12-07 00:26:26','',8,'/12',0,'revision','',0),(13,1,'2013-12-03 20