it organization</li>\r\n            <li>In August, one of our officers facilitated a series of strategic planning workshops for the Houston Food Policy Workgroup </li>\r\n        </ul>\r\n<h2>2013</h2>\r\n        <ul>\r\n            <li>In June, we held our second annual conference, “Honor the Land, Honor the People,” again drawing a diverse audience locally and from around the state</li>\r\n            <li>Collaborated with Metro Health on a sodium reduction grant that was awarded</li>\r\n            <li>Collaborated with Metro Health and other City partners to develop high standards for nutrition in the Pre-K for SA program</li>\r\n            <li>Partnering with  anti-hunger and social justice organizations to address the problems of hunger and diet-related disease in our city</li>\r\n            <li>Advising SAHA, along with AgriLife, Green Spaces Alliance,  and others on an urban farm/CSA for resident job training</li>\r\n            <li>Collaborating with City of San Antonio Department of Planning and Community Development on urban agriculture and other food related policies in the revision of the Unified Development Code</li>\r\n            <li>We continue to provide information to the community about policies and their effects on the food system</li>\r\n        </ul>','Our Work','','publish','closed','closed','','our-work','','','2013-12-05 13:52:08','2013-12-05 19:52:08','',0,'/?page_id=40',0,'page','',0),(41,3,'2013-12-05 13:45:01','2013-12-05 19:45:01','<h2>2010 - 2011</h2>\r\n        <ul>\r\n            <li>FPCSA, in partnership with the San Antonio Metropolitan Health District and the UTSA School of Public Policy, commissioned a Food Insecurity Assessment from UTSA’s Department of Demography. Using Census data and the USDA food atlas, as well as original survey and focus group findings, it provides a status of food insecurity in San Antonio, and opens the stage for questions and presents needs in the community</li>\r\n            <li>Nutrition graduate 